      "conditioning_notes": "`<CHAR_A>`'s love of rising to the moment shapes the spike beat — they don't freeze, they immediately move to action (\"We move the things that matter\"). Their fear of letting the group down surfaces in the quiet resolution: the \"not bad\" that they don't usually say is credit given because credit was earned, not deflection. `<CHAR_B>`'s love of holding it together and fear of losing control of the room shows up throughout — the schedule conflict at the top, the \"nobody panics\" self-narration in beat 6, the clean handoff to `<CHAR_C>` (\"do it\"). `<CHAR_C>`'s love of seeing the pattern first and fear of being wrong in public produce the spike beat's exact shape: Signal waited until certainty, *then* spoke — two weeks of watching before \"now I'm sure.\" The hideout location earns its function not through description but through behavior: characters are relaxed enough to bicker about lists, proprietary enough to treat the breach as a personal violation, and competent enough to respond without external help. The spike at tension 7 is sharp but brief, which is the whole grammar of steady_with_spike — the rest of the sequence earns the drop back down by showing the group actually handles it."
